00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:04.520
I've been studying
Berkshire for 20 years

00:02:04.520 --> 00:02:07.672
and began writing
about it in 1997,

00:02:07.672 --> 00:02:09.880
with the publication of the
essays of Warren Buffett.

00:02:11.450 --> 00:02:14.680
That grew out of a conference
I organized where I first

00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:19.210
met Warren, Berkshire's chairman
and CEO, who participated

00:02:19.210 --> 00:02:24.200
alongside his wife, Susan,
and Berkshire's vice

00:02:24.200 --> 00:02:26.160
chairman Charlie Munger.

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:30.360
Back then, Berkshire Hathaway
looked like a mutual fund,

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:32.440
primarily owning stocks.

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:37.240
And Warren Buffett was most
famous as a stock picker.

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:41.310
In earlier times, 80%
of Berkshire's value

00:02:41.310 --> 00:02:47.330
was in common stocks and only
20% in operational businesses.

00:02:47.330 --> 00:02:49.930
Today, the mix is
the other way around.

00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:54.680
80% of Berkshire's value is in
its 50 operating subsidiaries

00:02:54.680 --> 00:02:56.905
and only 20% in common stocks.

00:02:58.200 --> 00:03:01.390
Berkshire is today America's
fifth largest corporation.

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:06.290
Marking its fiftieth anniversary
under Warren's leadership

00:03:06.290 --> 00:03:09.640
next year, it is a microcosm
of corporate America.

00:03:10.670 --> 00:03:13.150
And its management
principles are

00:03:13.150 --> 00:03:16.960
as impressive as Buffett's
investment acumen,

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:18.715
though they are far
less appreciated.

00:03:20.690 --> 00:03:25.390
And now that Buffett
is 54, however, people

00:03:25.390 --> 00:03:28.680
wonder what will happen to
Berkshire when he's gone.

00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:31.630
Is there something so
special about Buffett

00:03:31.630 --> 00:03:33.955
that his departure will
spell Berkshire's demise?

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:37.810
Most people think that there is.

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:40.510
"The New York Times" last
year portrayed Buffett

00:03:40.510 --> 00:03:44.790
as having a, quote,
"irreplaceable magic touch."

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:46.870
"The Economist"
this year lamented

00:03:46.870 --> 00:03:48.700
that Berkshire was
down to, quote,

00:03:48.700 --> 00:03:51.490
"playing out the last hand."

00:03:51.490 --> 00:03:53.570
Such views are paradoxical.

00:03:53.570 --> 00:03:58.170
Buffett's goal has been to
build a lasting corporation.

00:03:58.170 --> 00:04:01.610
And yet, even fans like these
think the company cannot

00:04:01.610 --> 00:04:03.700
survive without him.

00:04:03.700 --> 00:04:06.620
So I researched
this question and I

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:09.160
found the inverse to be true.

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:12.060
That there's something so
special about Berkshire

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:15.220
that it can prosper even
without Warren Buffett.

00:04:16.850 --> 00:04:20.769
I conclude that Buffett's
greatest single achievement,

00:04:20.769 --> 00:04:25.270
more than vast fortune
and generous philanthropy,

00:04:25.270 --> 00:04:28.020
is creating an organization
larger than himself.

00:04:29.930 --> 00:04:33.150
True, Buffett may
epitomize Berkshire,

00:04:33.150 --> 00:04:35.420
but it is far from
a one-man show.

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:40.590
First, there is a
deep managerial bench,

00:04:40.590 --> 00:04:44.075
dozens of outstanding executives
who helped build Berkshire.

00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:49.920
For my research, Buffett gave
permission for them to help me.

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:53.460
And they did, many of them
through interviews, surveys,

00:04:53.460 --> 00:04:56.360
and some even commented
on the manuscript.

00:04:56.360 --> 00:04:58.732
A dozen are joining
me on the book tour.

00:04:58.732 --> 00:05:00.190
It's an impressive
group of people.

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:04.430
A second group are
Berkshire's directors,

00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:07.600
many who also helped me, like
former Microsoft executive

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:12.590
Charlotte Guyman, Warren's
son, Howard, and especially

00:05:12.590 --> 00:05:17.081
Tom Murphy, who built Capital
Cities ABC into a media

00:05:17.081 --> 00:05:17.580
powerhouse.

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:21.930
Earlier this year at
Berkshire's annual meeting,

00:05:21.930 --> 00:05:25.430
I asked Warren who should
write the forward to the book.

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:27.380
He instantly said Tom Murphy.

00:05:28.570 --> 00:05:29.840
I asked why.

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:34.110
He said, Tom was his
role model as a manager.

00:05:34.110 --> 00:05:36.480
Warren said he'd
learned most of what

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:38.940
he knows about
management from Tom.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:44.270
These comments are
noteworthy because this book

00:05:44.270 --> 00:05:49.240
is the first about Buffett
as a manager, not as just

00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:52.530
an investor, and the
first about Berkshire

00:05:52.530 --> 00:05:56.895
as a corporate entity, not just
a portfolio of investments.

00:05:59.120 --> 00:06:04.800
And Tom's foreword, which
was read to you a moment ago,

00:06:04.800 --> 00:06:07.080
captures an important
theme of the book

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:10.725
and I've just put the same quote
you just heard on the screen.

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:18.140
"Most of what I've
learned about management,"

00:06:18.140 --> 00:06:20.300
Warren said, "I
learned from Murph.

00:06:20.300 --> 00:06:21.940
I kick myself
because I should have

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:25.240
applied the lessons
much earlier."

00:06:25.240 --> 00:06:27.980
Here's Tom's quote,
"From afar, it

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:29.620
looks like
Berkshire's businesses

00:06:29.620 --> 00:06:31.140
are very different
from each other.

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:36.200
But on close inspection, they're
united by cultural bonds."

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:40.680
This is the myopia that
commentators suffer from.

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:43.340
They concentrate
and overemphasize

00:06:43.340 --> 00:06:47.020
the diversity of the
businesses and underappreciate

00:06:47.020 --> 00:06:49.810
and sometimes overlook
the cultural unity.

00:06:53.210 --> 00:06:56.690
Berkshire subsidiaries
engage in a wide range

00:06:56.690 --> 00:07:01.210
of totally unrelated businesses,
insurance and paint, energy

00:07:01.210 --> 00:07:05.660
and housing, transportation
and food, jewelry

00:07:05.660 --> 00:07:06.900
and pig-feeding equipment.

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:13.160
They vary in size from fewer
than 1,000 employees at many,

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:16.205
like Ben Bridge Jeweler,
to more than 30,000

00:07:16.205 --> 00:07:17.080
at Fruit of the Loom.

00:07:18.510 --> 00:07:21.800
Annual revenues run between
300 million and one billion

00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:24.870
for most, and there are
eight whose revenues

00:07:24.870 --> 00:07:27.330
are so large that
if stood alone,

00:07:27.330 --> 00:07:28.810
they'd be Fortune 500 companies.

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:33.580
Profit margins are all over
the place, stretching from 1%

00:07:33.580 --> 00:07:37.060
at McLane, the logistics
supply chain manager,

00:07:37.060 --> 00:07:39.910
to 25% at BNSF Railway.

00:07:41.910 --> 00:07:44.230
Berkshire subsidiaries
were acquired at prices

00:07:44.230 --> 00:07:48.910
all over the map, way less than
a billion for Justin boots,

00:07:48.910 --> 00:07:53.620
2 billion for Shaw carpets, 9
billion for the Marmom group,

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:56.460
the conglomerate that Jay
and Robert Pritzker built.

00:07:58.130 --> 00:08:00.900
They were acquired
at varying multiples,

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:03.690
from cheap bargains for
the maker of Garanimals

00:08:03.690 --> 00:08:06.950
to princely premiums for
the likes of BH Energy.

00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:12.380
And Berkshire subsidiaries are
headquartered all over the map.

00:08:15.460 --> 00:08:18.900
Beneath that slide is a map of
the United States of America

00:08:18.900 --> 00:08:22.670
that in this picture
are not showing up,

00:08:22.670 --> 00:08:26.870
but they are in Massachusetts,
North Carolina, Tennessee,

00:08:26.870 --> 00:08:30.300
California,
Washington, all over,

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:32.164
more than half the
states of the country.

00:08:33.890 --> 00:08:36.640
This diversity can be
explained by the first sentence

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:38.190
of my book.

00:08:38.190 --> 00:08:40.850
Berkshire Hathaway
is an accident.

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:43.070
It has never had
a business plan.

00:08:43.070 --> 00:08:45.710
It doesn't believe
in strategic plans.

00:08:45.710 --> 00:08:49.180
It is purely opportunistic,
buying companies

00:08:49.180 --> 00:08:53.770
that fit its criteria
and gel with its culture.

00:08:56.780 --> 00:08:58.700
Berkshire has
disclosed what it seeks

00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:03.110
in its acquisitions since 1986,
when it ran an ad in the "Wall

00:09:03.110 --> 00:09:05.380
Street Journal"
stating its criteria.

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:09.540
Those criteria
have never changed,

00:09:09.540 --> 00:09:13.040
except for size, which went from
5 million in annual earnings

00:09:13.040 --> 00:09:15.890
back then to 75 million today.

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:21.240
Proven profitability, good
unleveraged returns on equity,

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:25.105
management in place, basic
businesses, and a fair price.

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:28.750
Berkshire often sites
Berkshire culture

00:09:28.750 --> 00:09:34.100
as part of what will enable
it to prosper without him,

00:09:34.100 --> 00:09:36.920
but he's never said
exactly what that culture

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:39.830
is or explained
where it comes from.

00:09:40.792 --> 00:09:41.750
That's where I come in.

00:09:43.110 --> 00:09:46.170
By defining and illustrating
Berkshire culture,

00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:49.350
my book contends
that this culture

00:09:49.350 --> 00:09:54.900
is Berkshire's most valuable and
durable competitive advantage,

00:09:54.900 --> 00:09:58.130
which will contribute to
its business longevity

00:09:58.130 --> 00:10:00.605
long after the
Warren Buffett era.

00:10:02.230 --> 00:10:06.920
Intuitively, people don't
expect conglomerates,

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:11.290
vast and diverse, to have
discernible corporate cultures,

00:10:11.290 --> 00:10:13.630
but Berkshire has
a distinctive one,

00:10:13.630 --> 00:10:16.425
based on a core set
of shared values.

00:10:17.780 --> 00:10:20.890
In my research, I
probed Berkshire's

00:10:20.890 --> 00:10:25.800
fifty main subsidiaries,
seeking to identify

00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:29.380
their corporate cultures,
looking at the practices

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:33.640
and beliefs that define
them, through legends, lore,

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:35.025
and the trials of transitions.

00:10:36.040 --> 00:10:38.290
I then scrutinized
these profiles,

00:10:38.290 --> 00:10:41.210
and as I did a pattern emerged.

00:10:41.210 --> 00:10:47.040
I saw recurring traits across
all of them, nine altogether,

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:51.660
all being intangible traits
that the subsidiaries

00:10:51.660 --> 00:10:53.740
turn into economic gain.

00:10:55.180 --> 00:10:57.800
In the book, by offering
individual snapshots

00:10:57.800 --> 00:11:01.850
of these fifty companies,
organized around those nine

00:11:01.850 --> 00:11:05.230
values, the book presents
a portrait of the whole.

00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:08.510
Let me highlight a
few of these traits.

00:11:11.390 --> 00:11:14.250
Berkshire subs
tend to be thrifty,

00:11:14.250 --> 00:11:17.640
some say frugal,
cheap, even tightwads.

00:11:18.830 --> 00:11:20.125
Geico is a great example.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:23.610
Its business model
is to be the low cost

00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:27.300
supplier of car insurance,
a standardized product

00:11:27.300 --> 00:11:30.030
that law requires people
to have and few people

00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:30.980
wish to splurge on.

00:11:32.170 --> 00:11:35.380
Geico turns those conditions
into a competitive advantage.

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:39.170
It doesn't pocket all the
savings from its thrift,

00:11:39.170 --> 00:11:42.040
but passes most on to customers.

00:11:42.040 --> 00:11:45.840
In fact, it caps it's
underwriting profit at 4%.

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:47.830
If profits would
be more than that,

00:11:47.830 --> 00:11:51.190
it lowers prices, delivering
value to its customers.

00:11:52.710 --> 00:11:55.020
This, of course,
is not altruism.

00:11:55.020 --> 00:12:00.730
That model grows market share,
increases total premiums,

00:12:00.730 --> 00:12:03.135
and enlarges aggregate profits.

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:10.370
All Berkshire subsidiaries
embrace the golden rule.

00:12:10.370 --> 00:12:14.010
Do unto others as you would
have them do unto you.

00:12:14.010 --> 00:12:15.840
Take Clayton Homes.

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:19.710
It is a leading lender
to lower-income families

00:12:19.710 --> 00:12:24.170
in the United States and also
manufactures the trailer homes

00:12:24.170 --> 00:12:27.220
that many of that cohort buy.

00:12:27.220 --> 00:12:29.210
It always looks out
for its customers.

00:12:30.320 --> 00:12:32.440
Here's an example of
how Jim Clayton, who

00:12:32.440 --> 00:12:34.545
founded the company,
treated his customers.

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:38.450
He sat down with
them and determined

00:12:38.450 --> 00:12:41.590
what their income was
and their resources,

00:12:41.590 --> 00:12:44.760
and then worked
backwards to build homes

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:47.250
and lend money to
meet their budgets.

00:12:49.330 --> 00:12:50.700
Integrity like this pays.

00:12:51.810 --> 00:12:54.600
Amid the financial
crisis of 2008,

00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:56.600
Clayton's peers were
uncovered lending

00:12:56.600 --> 00:13:00.580
to sketchy buyers who they lured
in with low teaser interest

00:13:00.580 --> 00:13:01.750
rates.

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:05.490
Those companies faltered
and many cratered

00:13:05.490 --> 00:13:07.280
during the financial crisis.

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:10.710
That enabled Clayton
to prosper, moving it

00:13:10.710 --> 00:13:13.240
from fourth in its
industry to number one.

00:13:14.910 --> 00:13:17.270
Integrity is so
central at Berkshire,

00:13:17.270 --> 00:13:22.750
that managers even remotely
threatening it are soon let go.

00:13:22.750 --> 00:13:25.390
Whether David Sokol,
once considered

00:13:25.390 --> 00:13:28.540
a probable successor
to Buffett, who

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:32.080
was alleged to have
engaged in insider trading,

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:36.320
or successive managers at
Benjamin Moore, who prepared

00:13:36.320 --> 00:13:39.310
to market paint through
big box retailers

00:13:39.310 --> 00:13:41.070
in violation of a
commitment Berkshire

00:13:41.070 --> 00:13:43.840
had made to its local
distributor network.

00:13:47.540 --> 00:13:50.950
Berkshire subs are earnest.

00:13:50.950 --> 00:13:53.575
They consider keeping a
promise to be sacrosanct.

00:13:55.270 --> 00:13:58.670
And they turn that moral
conviction into economic gain.

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:02.620
Examples are Berkshire's other
two big insurance companies,

00:14:02.620 --> 00:14:07.410
National Indemnity,
NICO, and Gen Re.

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:11.250
They insure large and unusual
risks, some spanning decades.

00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:16.080
These features render their
word in insurance policy

00:14:16.080 --> 00:14:17.010
a precious asset.

00:14:18.230 --> 00:14:20.840
For instance earlier
this year, NICO

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:24.886
insured an offer by
Quicken to pay $1 billion

00:14:24.886 --> 00:14:31.190
to anyone correctly predicting
the Men's NCAA 64 Tournament

00:14:31.190 --> 00:14:33.650
Bracket, the odds of
which are something

00:14:33.650 --> 00:14:36.340
like 1 in 126 billion.

00:14:36.340 --> 00:14:39.070
If you pick it, Quicken
probably doesn't

00:14:39.070 --> 00:14:42.490
have the billion dollars
to pay, but NICO does

00:14:42.490 --> 00:14:43.540
and it will pay up.

00:14:45.370 --> 00:14:48.995
The NICO, Gen Re business
model differs from Geico's.

00:14:50.040 --> 00:14:53.610
They don't put the money in
the pockets of customers.

00:14:53.610 --> 00:14:54.820
They pocket the profit.

00:14:54.820 --> 00:14:58.130
They charge premiums for the
kind of special commitments

00:14:58.130 --> 00:15:00.250
that these high-end
products entail.

00:15:01.740 --> 00:15:04.580
So Berkshire thus
generates value

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:06.960
from its high-end
businesses where

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:09.310
customers pay a premium
for earnestness.

00:15:13.700 --> 00:15:17.930
People prize autonomy
and complex businesses

00:15:17.930 --> 00:15:20.030
gain value from
hands-off oversight.

00:15:21.660 --> 00:15:24.580
Berkshire is thoroughly
decentralized,

00:15:24.580 --> 00:15:29.430
with subsidiary CEOs having
virtually unbridled discretion

00:15:29.430 --> 00:15:31.490
over all operational
and strategic decisions.

00:15:32.850 --> 00:15:35.827
Autonomy starts at the
top and trickles down

00:15:35.827 --> 00:15:38.035
throughout the subsidiaries
and in most subsidiaries,

00:15:38.035 --> 00:15:40.490
it tends to trickle
down across that.

00:15:42.120 --> 00:15:45.580
A conspicuous example
is The Pampered Chef,

00:15:45.580 --> 00:15:49.400
which sells its kitchen
gadgetry through 70,000

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:53.125
independent distributors, all
of whom call their own shots.

00:15:54.730 --> 00:15:57.980
Every CEO I interviewed
for the book

00:15:57.980 --> 00:16:01.065
emphasized the value of
autonomy at Berkshire.

00:16:02.750 --> 00:16:05.610
Jim Weber, the CEO of Brooks,
the running shoe company,

00:16:05.610 --> 00:16:08.180
put it this way in my
interview with him.

00:16:08.180 --> 00:16:11.530
Quote, "I've never had so
much autonomy in my career

00:16:11.530 --> 00:16:14.730
and never felt so accountable."

00:16:14.730 --> 00:16:20.600
Tom Manenti, the CEO of MiTek,
the construction material firm,

00:16:20.600 --> 00:16:22.910
spoke of the trickle down
rationale in my interview

00:16:22.910 --> 00:16:23.780
with him.

00:16:23.780 --> 00:16:26.735
Quote, "Berkshire and Buffett
give me total autonomy.

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:29.980
Being treated that
way makes it easy

00:16:29.980 --> 00:16:35.340
for me to treat our
managers the same way."

00:16:35.340 --> 00:16:39.950
In chapter 16, I conclude
with this sentence, quote,

00:16:39.950 --> 00:16:43.110
"Berkshire's secret to
managing a large complicated

00:16:43.110 --> 00:16:47.310
organization is to
manage parsimoniously,

00:16:47.310 --> 00:16:50.930
as little as possible.''

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:54.985
And finally Buffett is well
known as a long-term investor.

00:16:56.450 --> 00:17:00.340
But a more profound point
about time at Berkshire

00:17:00.340 --> 00:17:03.035
is that its horizon is forever.

00:17:05.160 --> 00:17:09.780
Unique among its arrivals
in the acquisition market,

00:17:09.780 --> 00:17:13.990
Berkshire has not sold a
subsidiary in 40 years.

00:17:16.140 --> 00:17:20.280
That sense of permanence
has great economic value,

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:24.290
whether to family
businesses wanting a legacy

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:26.129
or entrepreneurs
wanting security.

00:17:28.190 --> 00:17:30.950
The most dramatic
are subsidiaries

00:17:30.950 --> 00:17:35.390
I call corporate orphans,
those that were owned serially

00:17:35.390 --> 00:17:38.030
by leveraged buyout
operators, private equity

00:17:38.030 --> 00:17:39.985
firms, or bankruptcy trustees.

00:17:41.370 --> 00:17:46.530
The experience can make managers
ache for a permanent home.

00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:49.930
For example, the
recreational vehicle maker

00:17:49.930 --> 00:17:54.080
now called Forest River was
owned by three different LBO

00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:56.850
operators in a row
before being acquired

00:17:56.850 --> 00:17:58.730
by its current CEO, Pete Liegl.

00:18:00.030 --> 00:18:05.260
It raised funds in yet another
LBO, borrowed very costly debt,

00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:08.894
the LBO operators micromanaged
Pete and the company

00:18:08.894 --> 00:18:10.060
soon sailed into bankruptcy.

00:18:12.160 --> 00:18:14.980
Pete bought most of the
assets out of bankruptcy,

00:18:14.980 --> 00:18:17.600
rebuilt the company,
positioned it as number one

00:18:17.600 --> 00:18:20.110
in the industry, and then
sold it to Berkshire,

00:18:20.110 --> 00:18:23.040
where he continues to
expand, without debt,

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:25.990
with total autonomy,
and a permanent home.

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:31.085
So permanence is
Berkshire's bedrock.

00:18:32.260 --> 00:18:35.940
That is reason to believe
in Berkshire's future

00:18:35.940 --> 00:18:38.970
after Warren Buffett is gone.

00:18:38.970 --> 00:18:43.240
Now, the Warren Buffett
era continues of course,

00:18:43.240 --> 00:18:47.550
and may continue for
another decade or two,

00:18:47.550 --> 00:18:49.360
as Warren is in
very good health.

00:18:51.480 --> 00:18:54.760
Still, whenever it ends, as
I write in the book's closing

00:18:54.760 --> 00:18:58.750
passages, quote, "while it's
hard to imagine Berkshire

00:18:58.750 --> 00:19:02.560
without Buffett, it seems
wiser to believe in Berkshire

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:07.000
beyond Buffett, an institution
that transcends the man

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.182
and will be his legacy."

00:19:09.182 --> 00:19:10.890
I thank you very much
for your attention.

00:19:10.890 --> 00:19:13.397
I'd be delighted to have
questions from the audience.

00:19:13.397 --> 00:19:14.230
Thank you very much.

00:19:14.230 --> 00:19:18.320
[APPLAUSE]

