00:20:29.620 --> 00:20:31.210
AUDIENCE: As you
were closing this,

00:20:31.210 --> 00:20:35.992
you mentioned there was that
person who did the homes

00:20:35.992 --> 00:20:36.700
and then sold it.

00:20:38.310 --> 00:20:41.270
It came out of LBO three
times, and then they

00:20:41.270 --> 00:20:42.440
ended up selling it.

00:20:42.440 --> 00:20:44.300
Yeah, that one-- Forest River.

00:20:44.300 --> 00:20:46.560
So after he made a profit,
what was the benefit

00:20:46.560 --> 00:20:49.678
of going to
Berkshire after that?

00:20:51.172 --> 00:20:52.622
LARRY CUNNINGHAM: Capital.

00:20:52.622 --> 00:20:54.080
In order to grow
this company, it's

00:20:54.080 --> 00:20:56.480
a capital-intensive operation.

00:20:56.480 --> 00:20:58.020
It's a manufacturing operation.

00:20:58.020 --> 00:21:00.990
He's got plants in a variety of
states, distribution centers,

00:21:00.990 --> 00:21:01.490
and so on.

00:21:01.490 --> 00:21:03.870
And so in order to
grow, he needed capital.

00:21:03.870 --> 00:21:06.690
And his personal
experience with the LBO,

00:21:06.690 --> 00:21:09.040
and the company's experience
with LBOs before him

00:21:09.040 --> 00:21:13.210
showed that borrowing
large amounts of capital

00:21:13.210 --> 00:21:13.980
can be dangerous.

00:21:15.160 --> 00:21:19.530
So he did not want to go the
LBO route to get capital.

00:21:21.310 --> 00:21:25.310
I left out that-- I tell
in the book-- he had also

00:21:25.310 --> 00:21:27.150
taken the company
public at one point

00:21:27.150 --> 00:21:31.320
to gain capital, which also
provided a bit of a bruising

00:21:31.320 --> 00:21:32.080
experience.

00:21:32.080 --> 00:21:34.540
Short-term pressure to
deliver profits this quarter,

00:21:34.540 --> 00:21:36.560
and this half year,
and so on, were

00:21:36.560 --> 00:21:41.510
difficult to sustain in
the recreational vehicle

00:21:41.510 --> 00:21:43.030
manufacturing space.

00:21:43.030 --> 00:21:46.160
So this LP, he had just been
bruised-- borrowing money,

00:21:46.160 --> 00:21:48.320
raising equity in the
public capital markets.

00:21:48.320 --> 00:21:51.810
So once he righted the ship,
he needed more capital.

00:21:51.810 --> 00:21:54.620
And Berkshire was a
perfect place for him.

00:21:54.620 --> 00:21:56.890
Because there's
plenty of capital,

00:21:56.890 --> 00:21:59.760
and as long as you're generating
good returns on capital,

00:21:59.760 --> 00:22:01.450
you're likely to
get plenty more.

00:22:01.450 --> 00:22:06.380
And he has done a terrific
job in doing that.

00:22:06.380 --> 00:22:09.270
In his press release, when he
announced that transaction,

00:22:09.270 --> 00:22:12.170
emphasized that this
company will no longer

00:22:12.170 --> 00:22:14.066
be borrowing money.

00:22:14.066 --> 00:22:18.540
So it's all Berkshire
capital, and he's just

00:22:18.540 --> 00:22:19.540
doing a phenomenal job.

00:22:19.540 --> 00:22:20.830
And he's just one example.

00:22:20.830 --> 00:22:24.390
There are seven what I
call corporate orphans

00:22:24.390 --> 00:22:26.740
that I feature in that chapter.

00:22:26.740 --> 00:22:30.010
They pivot around that
same longing for a way

00:22:30.010 --> 00:22:33.180
to generate capital
without the shackles

00:22:33.180 --> 00:22:35.900
of either micromanagement
or short term-ism.

00:22:35.900 --> 00:22:37.410
Berkshire is one place.

00:22:37.410 --> 00:22:40.140
AUDIENCE: Recently, Berkshire
made some big investments

00:22:40.140 --> 00:22:44.090
in BYD in China and
Posco in South Korea.

00:22:44.090 --> 00:22:46.290
I was wondering, on a
going-forward basis,

00:22:46.290 --> 00:22:48.160
do you see more of that?

00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:51.540
And since culture is such
a big part of the business,

00:22:51.540 --> 00:22:53.780
how do they evaluate
the management

00:22:53.780 --> 00:22:58.389
with such different
cultural situations?

00:22:58.389 --> 00:22:59.930
LARRY CUNNINGHAM:
Excellent question.

00:22:59.930 --> 00:23:00.440
Thanks.

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:02.940
I would first draw a
distinction between common stock

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:06.070
investments like those two that
you mentioned, where Berkshire

00:23:06.070 --> 00:23:08.340
buys a minority
interest and doesn't

00:23:08.340 --> 00:23:11.890
have the full control
over those enterprises,

00:23:11.890 --> 00:23:14.060
and on the other
hand, the subsidiaries

00:23:14.060 --> 00:23:16.710
that it does fully
own and fully control.

00:23:18.910 --> 00:23:22.480
So the commitment of permanence
is to those companies

00:23:22.480 --> 00:23:24.180
that it fully controls
and fully owns.

00:23:24.180 --> 00:23:28.080
So when it bought See's Candy,
or Forest River, or Geico,

00:23:28.080 --> 00:23:29.520
the commitment
is, we will always

00:23:29.520 --> 00:23:31.020
own you and never sell you.

00:23:31.020 --> 00:23:31.910
You with me?

00:23:31.910 --> 00:23:36.026
So those minority common
stock positions, Berkshire

00:23:36.026 --> 00:23:37.900
and Buffett would prefer
to own them forever,

00:23:37.900 --> 00:23:40.460
but there's no
commitment of that sort.

00:23:40.460 --> 00:23:42.382
So if they deteriorate
economically,

00:23:42.382 --> 00:23:44.340
culturally, or for other
reasons, they're sold.

00:23:45.820 --> 00:23:49.470
And that explains
the subsidiaries.

00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:52.730
All but one are American
companies based in America

00:23:52.730 --> 00:23:56.525
with managerial
affinity to things

00:23:56.525 --> 00:23:58.900
Berkshire has been doing for
a long time and understands.

00:23:58.900 --> 00:24:03.520
The one exception is ISCAR,
short for Israeli Car Buy,

00:24:03.520 --> 00:24:07.840
which is based in Israel with
operations all over the world.

00:24:07.840 --> 00:24:10.710
And it's actually-- even
though it's a foreign company,

00:24:10.710 --> 00:24:12.580
it has a lot in
common with Berkshire.

00:24:12.580 --> 00:24:17.240
It's a large conglomerate, a
network of different companies.

00:24:17.240 --> 00:24:19.950
But when they went
and bought that,

00:24:19.950 --> 00:24:21.940
it was a very slow
transaction for Berkshire.

00:24:21.940 --> 00:24:25.480
Because he, Buffett,
and his inner circle

00:24:25.480 --> 00:24:31.220
had to learn about Israel,
management practice there,

00:24:31.220 --> 00:24:32.740
tax issues.

00:24:32.740 --> 00:24:34.750
So it took a lot longer.

00:24:34.750 --> 00:24:39.330
So with that backdrop,
I don't expect

00:24:39.330 --> 00:24:43.090
many immediate additional
acquisitions abroad.

00:24:43.090 --> 00:24:45.650
But I do predict in the book
that we will see that gradually

00:24:45.650 --> 00:24:46.540
in the coming years.

00:24:46.540 --> 00:24:50.310
But I think, in other words,
that the Berkshire model

00:24:50.310 --> 00:24:52.560
is scalable to the world.

00:24:52.560 --> 00:24:55.060
But I think it will take longer
to do that than it has taken

00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:57.285
to spread across
the United States.

00:24:57.285 --> 00:24:58.310
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:24:58.310 --> 00:25:01.620
One of my concerns
for Berkshire is

00:25:01.620 --> 00:25:07.130
that what if the successor
engages in empire building?

00:25:07.130 --> 00:25:13.510
So if they make some big,
major mistake in acquisition,

00:25:13.510 --> 00:25:18.300
then Berkshire is going to
underperform the [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:18.300 --> 00:25:19.740
So what's your take on that?

00:25:19.740 --> 00:25:21.530
LARRY CUNNINGHAM:
Yeah, I think so.

00:25:21.530 --> 00:25:24.430
I think the first thing to
appreciate about mistakes

00:25:24.430 --> 00:25:28.240
is that Berkshire has made a
lot of them in its history.

00:25:28.240 --> 00:25:30.910
And the first thing that the
successor and his community

00:25:30.910 --> 00:25:32.770
will need to remember
is that they're

00:25:32.770 --> 00:25:34.430
going to make them again.

00:25:34.430 --> 00:25:35.760
You with me?

00:25:35.760 --> 00:25:39.040
People should avoid-- I think
the one big risk for Berkshire

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:42.130
beyond Buffett is the nostalgia
trap, when people think, oh,

00:25:42.130 --> 00:25:43.640
Berkshire was so
wonderful before.

00:25:43.640 --> 00:25:45.430
Now there are
mistakes being made.

00:25:45.430 --> 00:25:46.760
So mistakes will be made.

00:25:46.760 --> 00:25:50.347
And I think people should
accept that the CEO will

00:25:50.347 --> 00:25:50.930
make mistakes.

00:25:52.200 --> 00:25:54.190
If the mistake
she or he makes is

00:25:54.190 --> 00:25:58.290
a mistake of violating
traditional Berkshire culture,

00:25:58.290 --> 00:25:59.981
undermining some of
these principles,

00:25:59.981 --> 00:26:02.230
then I think there would be
serious cause for concern.

00:26:02.230 --> 00:26:05.140
For example, if a
successor were to say,

00:26:05.140 --> 00:26:09.182
we are not going to continue
to own Forest River.

00:26:09.182 --> 00:26:10.140
We've had enough of it.

00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:11.420
We're going to sell it.

00:26:11.420 --> 00:26:13.320
If they did that, that's
more than a mistake.

00:26:13.320 --> 00:26:16.320
That would be a breach, I
think, of Berkshire culture.

00:26:16.320 --> 00:26:19.260
And if that kind of
decision were made,

00:26:19.260 --> 00:26:22.140
the CEO began selling
off subsidiaries,

00:26:22.140 --> 00:26:24.690
that would destroy Berkshire,
it would undermine, at least,

00:26:24.690 --> 00:26:27.030
a very important
fundamental principle.

00:26:27.030 --> 00:26:29.315
I don't think a
person will do that.

00:26:29.315 --> 00:26:30.440
There may be some pressure.

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:33.100
Activist shareholders
might pressure a successor

00:26:33.100 --> 00:26:36.330
to sell this company, that
company, or the other one

00:26:36.330 --> 00:26:39.490
to get the cash rather than
having these companies sit

00:26:39.490 --> 00:26:41.850
inside the broad conglomerate.

00:26:41.850 --> 00:26:44.240
I don't think the activist
shareholders will succeed

00:26:44.240 --> 00:26:46.300
in that kind of
campaign, however,

00:26:46.300 --> 00:26:49.120
because all the CEOs
of Berkshire companies

00:26:49.120 --> 00:26:51.780
understand these
values, buy into them,

00:26:51.780 --> 00:26:54.946
and one of them who's leading
the company will sustain them.

00:26:54.946 --> 00:26:56.570
Moreover, the board
of directors that I

00:26:56.570 --> 00:26:58.540
refer to understand
these values,

00:26:58.540 --> 00:27:00.950
appreciate their
importance, and will likely

00:27:00.950 --> 00:27:02.510
try to enforce them.

00:27:02.510 --> 00:27:04.220
Indeed, the chairman
of the board

00:27:04.220 --> 00:27:06.540
is very likely be
Warren's son Howard,

00:27:06.540 --> 00:27:09.620
whose job, Warren
has said, will be

00:27:09.620 --> 00:27:13.050
to remind everyone, if
needed, of Berkshire culture.

00:27:13.050 --> 00:27:15.060
So there is some risk there.

00:27:15.060 --> 00:27:18.050
But I think the
plan that's in place

00:27:18.050 --> 00:27:21.496
is the best reasonably possible
plan to protect against it.

00:27:21.496 --> 00:27:23.390
