have been successful investors

00:28:08.910 --> 00:28:10.500
on their own before
joining Berkshire

00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:11.580
five or seven years ago.

00:28:11.580 --> 00:28:15.530
They have now continued to
show their investment prowess,

00:28:15.530 --> 00:28:18.940
sometimes beating Warren
Buffett in those years.

00:28:18.940 --> 00:28:21.040
So I've got a lot of
confidence in those fellas,

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:23.820
and obviously Warren
does and the board does.

00:28:23.820 --> 00:28:26.590
I think their job,
the hardest thing

00:28:26.590 --> 00:28:31.140
they will have to deal
with is the anchor of size.

00:28:31.140 --> 00:28:34.490
It's very difficult with
that amount of money

00:28:34.490 --> 00:28:39.210
to pick stocks and continue
to outperform the market.

00:28:39.210 --> 00:28:43.510
Moreover, Berkshire's
investment portfolio

00:28:43.510 --> 00:28:44.910
is highly concentrated.

00:28:44.910 --> 00:28:51.010
Of that $120 billion odd, 70% of
it is in just seven companies--

00:28:51.010 --> 00:28:59.320
American Express, Wells Fargo,
IBM, Coca Cola, Exxon Mobile.

00:28:59.320 --> 00:29:03.080
Just seven companies make
up 70% of the portfolio.

00:29:03.080 --> 00:29:06.670
Now, in the next
5, 10, or 15 years,

00:29:06.670 --> 00:29:09.260
the economic characteristics
of one or more of those

00:29:09.260 --> 00:29:10.140
may deteriorate.

00:29:10.140 --> 00:29:13.190
And it may be time to sell.

00:29:13.190 --> 00:29:16.080
Whoever has to make
that decision, that's

00:29:16.080 --> 00:29:18.690
a huge challenge to decide,
OK, we're selling Coca Cola.

00:29:18.690 --> 00:29:21.690
That's going to be a very
hard decision to make.

00:29:21.690 --> 00:29:24.160
Moreover, having
made it, then they

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:27.885
have to figure out what to do
with $10, $15, or $20 billion

00:29:27.885 --> 00:29:30.080
in one fell swoop.

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:32.860
It's very rare to find
acquisition opportunities

00:29:32.860 --> 00:29:35.770
of that scale, as
Berkshire repeatedly shows.

00:29:35.770 --> 00:29:37.750
It's eager to find such
things, but they simply

00:29:37.750 --> 00:29:38.950
don't come up very often.

00:29:38.950 --> 00:29:41.040
So Todd, Ted, or
whomever is running

00:29:41.040 --> 00:29:43.580
that portfolio is going to have
a very hard job of deciding

00:29:43.580 --> 00:29:44.750
what to do.

00:29:44.750 --> 00:29:47.330
Probably, it will
mean buying a larger

00:29:47.330 --> 00:29:49.220
number of smaller stakes.

00:29:49.220 --> 00:29:53.550
In other words, making it look
more and more like the market.

00:29:53.550 --> 00:29:56.061
I think Todd and Ted,
they will do fine.

00:29:56.061 --> 00:29:58.310
But it's going to be a very
different job than the job

00:29:58.310 --> 00:29:59.768
Warren has had,
and there are going

00:29:59.768 --> 00:30:01.135
to be some heavy challenges.

00:30:02.625 --> 00:30:04.750
AUDIENCE: I think part of
the question is answered,

00:30:04.750 --> 00:30:05.860
but I'll ask it anyway.

00:30:05.860 --> 00:30:10.680
How do you compare Ted and
Todd's performance so far

00:30:10.680 --> 00:30:15.005
to, say, Warren Buffett's
investing prowess about 20,

00:30:15.005 --> 00:30:16.164
25 years ago?

00:30:16.164 --> 00:30:17.580
I think both of
them are managing,

00:30:17.580 --> 00:30:19.230
what, $7 or $10
billion together?

00:30:20.380 --> 00:30:24.070
I'm thinking if you went
back to '70s or '80s

00:30:24.070 --> 00:30:26.770
when Warren was
managing that portfolio.

00:30:26.770 --> 00:30:28.850
How do you compare the two?

00:30:28.850 --> 00:30:31.020
Do you have any insights
or additional thoughts?

00:30:33.352 --> 00:30:37.050
LARRY CUNNINGHAM: They
are experienced investors

00:30:37.050 --> 00:30:38.240
with a good track record.

00:30:38.240 --> 00:30:40.290
At Berkshire,
they, I think, were

00:30:40.290 --> 00:30:43.260
responsible for
selecting DirecTV,

00:30:43.260 --> 00:30:46.610
which had a good run
and then a big payout,

00:30:46.610 --> 00:30:48.740
and also for DaVita
Health, which

00:30:48.740 --> 00:30:53.580
is developing kidney
dialysis equipment.

00:30:53.580 --> 00:30:55.940
And both of them
are very successful.

00:30:55.940 --> 00:30:59.730
So it's hard to compare,
are those like Coca Cola,

00:30:59.730 --> 00:31:01.580
or like Cap Cities ABC?

00:31:01.580 --> 00:31:02.739
I don't know.

00:31:02.739 --> 00:31:05.030
It's different eras, it's
different types of businesses

00:31:05.030 --> 00:31:05.530
and so on.

00:31:05.530 --> 00:31:07.010
But the track record is strong.

00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:12.210
There's a joke floating
around on Twitter this morning

00:31:12.210 --> 00:31:14.622
about this person is the
Warren Buffett of Canada,

00:31:14.622 --> 00:31:16.580
and this person is the
Warren Buffett of China,

00:31:16.580 --> 00:31:18.705
and this person is the
Warren Buffett of Australia.

00:31:18.705 --> 00:31:22.280
And someone from MarketWatch
asked me, is it good to say,

00:31:22.280 --> 00:31:24.160
you're the Warren
Buffett from this place,

00:31:24.160 --> 00:31:25.660
and that place, and
the other place?

00:31:25.660 --> 00:31:27.640
And my response,
thanks to my wife,

00:31:27.640 --> 00:31:29.360
was there's only
one Warren Buffett.

00:31:31.460 --> 00:31:33.809
As good as Tad and Ted
are, they're not Warren,and

00:31:33.809 --> 00:31:35.100
they're not going to be Warren.

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:37.100
But I think they'll do
just fine for themselves.

00:31:37.709 --> 00:31:39.500
AUDIENCE: What do you
think about this idea

00:31:39.500 --> 00:31:41.240
that software is
eating the world,

00:31:41.240 --> 00:31:43.770
and that basically,
a lot of businesses

00:31:43.770 --> 00:31:50.570
that have been sort of immune to
technological change for a time

00:31:50.570 --> 00:31:52.070
basically get more
and more software

00:31:52.070 --> 00:31:54.710
that will determine their
eventual profit margin?

00:31:56.222 --> 00:31:57.930
When I look at the
list of the companies,

00:31:57.930 --> 00:32:01.090
they seem the ones that are a
little bit insulated, maybe,

00:32:01.090 --> 00:32:01.590
right now.

00:32:01.590 --> 00:32:04.820
But down the road, do you
think that's going to change?

00:32:06.200 --> 00:32:08.990
LARRY CUNNINGHAM:
Every competitor

00:32:08.990 --> 00:32:12.720
faces risks of
technological change,

00:32:12.720 --> 00:32:15.280
and disruption, and
even obsolescence.

00:32:15.280 --> 00:32:16.780
That's been true
throughout history.

00:32:16.780 --> 00:32:18.363
And we probably are
living in a period

00:32:18.363 --> 00:32:20.740
of particularly rapid change.

00:32:20.740 --> 00:32:24.660
Even companies in
Berkshire's family face this.

00:32:26.290 --> 00:32:31.920
And See's Candies, for example,
is an excellent confectioner

00:32:31.920 --> 00:32:34.740
with a terrific
product and brand name,

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:36.740
but it's been kind of regional.

00:32:36.740 --> 00:32:40.710
And they have not been able to
expand it despite the internet.

00:32:40.710 --> 00:32:41.760
And they need to.

00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:46.100
And they are working on
that, but it's going slowly.

00:32:46.100 --> 00:32:48.330
The Pampered Chef to
which I referred earlier

00:32:48.330 --> 00:32:51.350
sells its products
through these 70,000

00:32:51.350 --> 00:32:52.470
independent distributors.

00:32:52.470 --> 00:32:55.230
Traditionally, these people
have parties at their homes

00:32:55.230 --> 00:32:58.400
and invite friends and
neighbors to test out the stuff

00:32:58.400 --> 00:32:59.400
and use it.

00:32:59.400 --> 00:33:02.440
And it's a quaint, delightful,
wonderful business model

00:33:02.440 --> 00:33:04.420
that was very
successful in the '90s,

00:33:04.420 --> 00:33:06.990
but is less successful now.

00:33:06.990 --> 00:33:09.200
They need to figure
out how to navigate

00:33:09.200 --> 00:33:11.050
the current environment.

00:33:11.050 --> 00:33:13.209
Berkshire has acquired
a lot of newspapers,

00:33:13.209 --> 00:33:14.750
just in the last
three or four years,

00:33:14.750 --> 00:33:17.680
a business that is
rapidly changing.

00:33:17.680 --> 00:33:21.510
So many Berkshire companies
face this kind of challenge.

00:33:21.510 --> 00:33:25.490
What's special about Berkshire
is that it sticks with them

00:33:25.490 --> 00:33:30.230
and attempts to help ride out
the onslaught, and adapt to it,

00:33:30.230 --> 00:33:33.010
and change, and evolve,
rather than just sell it.

00:33:33.010 --> 00:33:36.390
So as long as other
members of the family

00:33:36.390 --> 00:33:39.950
maintain their
competitive advantages

00:33:39.950 --> 00:33:43.900
and generate capital to
support those that need it,

00:33:43.900 --> 00:33:45.635
the whole can be sustained.

00:33:46.740 --> 00:33:49.850
And the idea of keeping even
those that are struggling

00:33:49.850 --> 00:33:53.720
is so fundamental to the
company's DNA and its success

00:33:53.720 --> 00:33:59.270
that anybody who takes over the
CEO job will have to see that.

00:34:00.410 --> 00:34:03.440
AUDIENCE: So during
the financial crisis,

00:34:03.440 --> 00:34:10.600
AIG was destroyed just because
a small part of the company.

00:34:10.600 --> 00:34:13.199
It was the derivative
department.

00:34:13.199 --> 00:34:15.159
So do you see that
there might be

00:34:15.159 --> 00:34:18.190
something like
that in Berkshire?

00:34:21.060 --> 00:34:23.630
Some major mistake
that just destroys

00:34:23.630 --> 00:34:25.870
all of the shareholder value?

00:34:25.870 --> 00:34:26.870
LARRY CUNNINGHAM: Right.

00:34:26.870 --> 00:34:27.780
Yeah, that's right.

00:34:27.780 --> 00:34:30.409
It was the Financial
Products Division at AIG

00:34:30.409 --> 00:34:33.730
that had expanded a portfolio
of credit default swaps

00:34:33.730 --> 00:34:35.909
that turned out to be toxic.

00:34:35.909 --> 00:34:40.530
And Ben Bernanke, the Chairman
of the Federal Reserve

00:34:40.530 --> 00:34:42.659
at the time,
described the company

00:34:42.659 --> 00:34:45.179
as being an insurance company
with a hedge fund on top.

00:34:45.179 --> 00:34:49.920
That FP division had absorbed
enormous risks and became,

00:34:49.920 --> 00:34:52.670
really, a cancer that
threatened to metastasise

00:34:52.670 --> 00:34:55.350
across the company
until the great surgeons

00:34:55.350 --> 00:34:58.340
at the federal government
did serious surgery

00:34:58.340 --> 00:35:00.460
and saved the victim
in a certain way.

00:35:01.600 --> 00:35:05.070
I wrote a book about that
with the former chairman

00:35:05.070 --> 00:35:07.410
of the company
and attribute that

00:35:07.410 --> 00:35:12.680
to a problem of internal
control with the company,

00:35:12.680 --> 00:35:16.030
that that group should not
have been able to do that.

00:35:16.030 --> 00:35:18.320
There should have been
monitoring and oversight

00:35:18.320 --> 00:35:21.010
of that group that had
simply disappeared.

00:35:22.100 --> 00:35:24.080
So it's a great and
important question.

00:35:24.080 --> 00:35:27.160
Every company needs
to have some mechanism

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:30.000
to identify potential
rogues in their midst

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.190
to eliminate that
kind of problem.

00:35:32.190 --> 00:35:34.920
And I do think
Berkshire has that.

00:35:34.920 --> 00:35:38.140
It's not a traditional
internal control structure

00:35:38.140 --> 00:35:41.620
with lots of layers
of oversight,

00:35:41.620 --> 00:35:46.920
and thick reporting protocols,
and second guessing its own

00:35:46.920 --> 00:35:50.800
that you would see today at
AIG, or at IBM, or probably

00:35:50.800 --> 00:35:52.220
even at Google.

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:55.020
But instead, this
approach-- what

00:35:55.020 --> 00:35:58.690
I call a trust-based approach
to corporate governance--

00:35:58.690 --> 00:36:01.420
relies heavily on that
autonomy principle.

00:36:01.420 --> 00:36:06.320
So at Berkshire headquarters,
there is no direct mechanism

00:36:06.320 --> 00:36:10.570
to monitor, let's say, the
Cyprus Insurance Company.

00:36:10.570 --> 00:36:13.180
What exactly are
they underwriting?

00:36:13.180 --> 00:36:16.360
Or even, for that
matter, Gen Re.

00:36:16.360 --> 00:36:19.540
Gen Re got into
considerable difficulty

00:36:19.540 --> 00:36:22.670
shortly after Berkshire
acquired it in the late '90s

00:36:22.670 --> 00:36:26.970
because it had underwritten
a concentrated level

00:36:26.970 --> 00:36:31.020
of super catastrophic risk
of biological, chemical,

00:36:31.020 --> 00:36:33.520
and nuclear disaster.

00:36:33.520 --> 00:36:40.620
And after 9/11, it
faced insolvency.

00:36:40.620 --> 00:36:44.280
And if Berkshire hadn't acquired
it a couple years before,

00:36:44.280 --> 00:36:46.080
it would have gone under.

00:36:46.080 --> 00:36:48.360
Berkshire put into
place senior management

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:51.140
who vowed to correct
that problem,

00:36:51.140 --> 00:36:53.700
eliminate those kinds
of concentrated risk,

00:36:53.700 --> 00:36:56.020
and maintain a culture
in which that will not

00:36:56.020 --> 00:36:57.950
be permitted to happen again.

00:36:57.950 --> 00:37:02.260
So all across Berkshire,
that kind of autonomy, trust

00:37:02.260 --> 00:37:04.440
is baked into the company.

00:37:04.440 --> 00:37:06.430
A rogue can show up anywhere.

00:37:07.720 --> 00:37:13.040
But I think-- I am convinced
that the governance,

00:37:13.040 --> 00:37:16.410
the control model at Berkshire,
this trust-based model,

00:37:16.410 --> 00:37:18.360
does work at the company.

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:23.790
So I have a very
low level of concern

00:37:23.790 --> 00:37:28.200
that you would see
a financial products

00:37:28.200 --> 00:37:29.970
division like AIG
had at Berkshire.

00:37:31.189 --> 00:37:33.230
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
the importance of culture

00:37:33.230 --> 00:37:35.425
in the companies that
Berkshire acquires.

00:37:37.170 --> 00:37:38.550
Does Berkshire
look for companies

00:37:38.550 --> 00:37:41.930
that already bring the
same cultural values to it,

00:37:41.930 --> 00:37:46.750
or do the subsidiaries
evolve to that same point?

00:37:46.750 --> 00:37:49.210
And how does a large
company like Berkshire

00:37:49.210 --> 00:37:50.885
preserve its culture?

00:37:50.885 --> 00:37:53.150
LARRY CUNNINGHAM: That's
an excellent question.

00:37:53.150 --> 00:37:54.690
My answer is that
it's iterative.

00:37:55.750 --> 00:37:58.210
When Berkshire scouts
for acquisitions,

00:37:58.210 --> 00:38:01.170
or when acquisition proposals
are presented to it, primarily

00:38:01.170 --> 00:38:04.680
to Warren, he has a sense
that the company needs

00:38:04.680 --> 00:38:08.270
to be frugal, earnest,
entrepreneurial,

00:38:08.270 --> 00:38:11.800
prepared for autonomy, and
interested in the long term.

00:38:11.800 --> 00:38:15.770
So it's a mental checklist
that he has that companies that

00:38:15.770 --> 00:38:19.240
fit the Berkshire
mold will also have.

00:38:19.240 --> 00:38:21.820
Then when they join
the Berkshire family,

00:38:21.820 --> 00:38:24.350
those values get reinforced.

00:38:24.350 --> 00:38:27.930
And so the family is, in
that way, self-sustaining.

00:38:30.740 --> 00:38:34.550
Then that is sui
generis in the sense

00:38:34.550 --> 00:38:37.485
of being almost automatic.

00:38:38.490 --> 00:38:41.920
Sure, people need to
buy into the principles

00:38:41.920 --> 00:38:44.460
and need to reinforce
them through their words

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:45.172
and actions.

00:38:45.172 --> 00:38:46.755
But I think you see
that in abundance.

00:38:47.950 --> 00:38:55.710
But it could unravel if the
wrong leadership assumed

00:38:55.710 --> 00:38:58.660
control and decided that these
values were not important

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:03.980
anymore, and began to
micromanage the CEOs,

00:39:03.980 --> 00:39:07.300
to sell subsidiaries,
or to skate

00:39:07.300 --> 00:39:12.060
close to the edge of integrity,
and so on, then the culture

00:39:12.060 --> 00:39:12.910
could unwind.

00:39:12.910 --> 00:39:17.130
And you'd have simply
another conglomerate

00:39:17.130 --> 00:39:20.180
like Litton Industries, or
Gulf and Western, or United

00:39:20.180 --> 00:39:22.920
Technologies, or General
Electric, what have you.

00:39:22.920 --> 00:39:25.410
And what is special about
Berkshire would dissolve.

00:39:25.410 --> 00:39:28.710
AUDIENCE: You've written
about Ben Graham, the essays

00:39:28.710 --> 00:39:33.600
of Warren Buffett, and
then AIG in this book.

00:39:33.600 --> 00:39:36.330
Through all your years of
interacting with everyone,

00:39:36.330 --> 00:39:40.870
what would you say is one thing
you learned that you would like

00:39:40.870 --> 00:39:44.220
to share with us about
investing, and then one thing

00:39:44.220 --> 00:39:48.439
that you learned that could
apply to just life in general?

00:39:48.439 --> 00:39:50.480
LARRY CUNNINGHAM: I'll
take the second one first,

00:39:50.480 --> 00:39:51.130
because it's easier.

00:39:51.130 --> 00:39:51.755
It's integrity.

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:56.570
Life in general-- just being
honest, being forthright,

00:39:56.570 --> 00:40:02.430
keeping your word, treating
your promises as sacrosanct,

00:40:02.430 --> 00:40:04.280
staying in the middle
of the playing field,

00:40:04.280 --> 00:40:09.250
to use an athletic
analogy, avoiding skating

00:40:09.250 --> 00:40:11.150
on the edge of thin ice.

00:40:11.150 --> 00:40:15.450
I like Buffett's
admonition on this point

00:40:15.450 --> 00:40:23.580
that he came up with in the
late 1980s Salomon Brothers bond

00:40:23.580 --> 00:40:24.470
trading scandal.

00:40:24.470 --> 00:40:27.630
That was an investment banking
firm brought to its knees

00:40:27.630 --> 00:40:33.430
by a few rogue traders who tried
to corner the US Treasury bond

00:40:33.430 --> 00:40:39.210
market, and it threatened
the life of the firm.

00:40:39.210 --> 00:40:42.470
And in trying to rehabilitate
this institution, which

00:40:42.470 --> 00:40:45.050
had been a venerable
banking house,

00:40:45.050 --> 00:40:48.560
the board asked Warren, who had
bought stock in the company,

00:40:48.560 --> 00:40:49.970
to become chairman.

00:40:49.970 --> 00:40:53.160
And he stepped into that
role with great turmoil.

00:40:53.160 --> 00:40:56.980
And the first thing he did was
clean out the top management

00:40:56.980 --> 00:41:00.380
ranks and install three of
his own chosen executives

00:41:00.380 --> 00:41:03.570
to be CEO, general
counsel, and CFO.

00:41:03.570 --> 00:41:07.700
And these were people
with exemplary reputations

00:41:07.700 --> 00:41:10.360
for ethical business leadership.

00:41:10.360 --> 00:41:14.910
He then stood up and
told a press gathering,

00:41:14.910 --> 00:41:18.600
and wrote a memo to
the workers, that

00:41:18.600 --> 00:41:23.870
said, lose money for the firm,
and I will be understanding.

00:41:25.140 --> 00:41:28.625
Lose a shred of reputation for
the firm, and I'll be ruthless.

00:41:30.690 --> 00:41:32.280
I'm getting chills
just saying that.

00:41:32.280 --> 00:41:33.071
Did you get chills?

00:41:35.620 --> 00:41:37.820
And his test for that,
in case you needed it,

00:41:37.820 --> 00:41:41.624
was in any action you're
about to take-- any insurance

00:41:41.624 --> 00:41:43.665
policy you're going to
underwrite, any bond trade

00:41:43.665 --> 00:41:46.690
you're going to do, any
leasing transaction, any sale

00:41:46.690 --> 00:41:51.080
of a mobile home-- he said,
think about that decision,

00:41:51.080 --> 00:41:54.870
your activity, being
written up by a journalist

00:41:54.870 --> 00:41:59.020
on the front page-- or now your
web page-- of your hometown

00:41:59.020 --> 00:42:01.750
paper by a smart journalist.

00:42:03.190 --> 00:42:06.550
Would you do it knowing all
your friends and neighbors

00:42:06.550 --> 00:42:08.220
know this is what you did?

00:42:08.220 --> 00:42:10.620
That's a pretty good test.

00:42:11.770 --> 00:42:13.850
That's my answer to
your second question.

00:42:13.850 --> 00:42:16.810
Life lessons to me, lessons I'd
like to share with my children,

00:42:16.810 --> 00:42:18.950
integrity is really number one.

00:42:18.950 --> 00:42:21.265
I like being thrifty,
and I like autonomy,

00:42:21.265 --> 00:42:22.370
and I like permanence.

00:42:22.370 --> 00:42:23.290
They're all very important.

00:42:23.290 --> 00:42:24.665
But if you had to
boil it down, I

00:42:24.665 --> 00:42:27.710
think integrity is number one.

00:42:27.710 --> 00:42:30.810
Investing lessons, I
admire the tradition

00:42:30.810 --> 00:42:33.960
of value investing
begun by Ben Graham,

00:42:33.960 --> 00:42:37.840
sustained by and modified by
the likes of Phil Fisher, who

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:41.000
wrote the great book "Common
Stocks And Uncommon Profits,"

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:48.910
and by Charlie Munger, Warren's
partner since the '70s or '60s,

00:42:48.910 --> 00:42:51.620
and Warren himself,
who emphasized

00:42:51.620 --> 00:42:53.890
fundamental,
substantive analysis

00:42:53.890 --> 00:42:55.110
of particular positions.

00:42:55.110 --> 00:42:56.205
It's hard homework.

00:42:56.205 --> 00:42:57.910
It's not easy to do.

00:42:57.910 --> 00:43:01.730
It requires research and effort.

00:43:01.730 --> 00:43:04.400
But I admire that tradition.

00:43:04.400 --> 00:43:08.970
So I guess the one thing I
learned from that is investing

00:43:08.970 --> 00:43:13.380
is a significant undertaking.

00:43:13.380 --> 00:43:15.280
And if you're not
prepared for it, it's OK.

00:43:15.280 --> 00:43:20.150
But then the best thing to
do with your personal excess

00:43:20.150 --> 00:43:26.280
capital is to buy an index fund,
like the ones run by Vanguard

00:43:26.280 --> 00:43:28.960
or Fidelity, so that you don't
really have to do the work.

00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:30.400
You enjoy the market return.

00:43:30.400 --> 00:43:33.600
Good and bad overall,
long term probably good.

00:43:33.600 --> 00:43:37.780
But if you're going to
do tailored investing,

00:43:37.780 --> 00:43:39.670
then I like the value
investing model,

00:43:39.670 --> 00:43:42.240
fundamental [? substantive ?]
model in comparison, say,

00:43:42.240 --> 00:43:47.860
with trying to track patterns
in performance over time,

00:43:47.860 --> 00:43:50.990
or trying to time the
market on a daily basis,

00:43:50.990 --> 00:43:52.690
getting in and out
at the right times,

00:43:52.690 --> 00:43:55.250
and other techniques
that don't appeal to me.

00:43:55.250 --> 00:44:00.290
So I've been a great devotee
of that Graham Fisher Buffett

00:44:00.290 --> 00:44:01.694
Munger crowd.

00:44:01.694 --> 00:44:03.110
MALE SPEAKER: Thank
you very much.

00:44:03.110 --> 00:44:04.960
That was fascinating.

